# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: connie-mack
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The **1886 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1886.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the Chicago White Stockings and the St.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns as regular season champions of the National League and American Association, respectively.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the third World's Championship Series on October 18 and ended with Game 6 on October 23, in what was a best-of-seven-playoff.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The Browns defeated the White Stockings, four games to two, capturing their first World's Championship Series.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Over the offseason, the National League's Buffalo Bisons transfer into the minor league International League and Providence Grays fold.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The two open spots are filled by the newly enfranchised Kansas City Cowboys and Washington Nationals.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The 1886 schedule consisted of 140 games for all American Association teams and 126 games for all National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Each AA team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams, while each NL team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other seven teams.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Both the AA's 140-game format and NL's 126-game format were newly-implementation for the 1886 season, each replacing the 112-game, 16 games against the other seven teams format that both leagues had from 1884 and 1885.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The NL would adopt the AA's format in 1888, and each league would use this 140-game format until 1892.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring six teams, while National League Opening Day took place on April 29, also featuring six teams.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The 1886 World's Championship Series took place between October 18 and October 23.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing the Brooklyn Grays of the American Association (which was informally referred to as the "Beer & Whiskey League" due to its openness on alcohol, compared to the National League) to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] 28 tie games (13 in AA, 15 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:connie-mack/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Grays of the American Association begin hosting Sunday games, playing 14 games at Ridgewood Park in Ridgewood, New York on May 2, 16, 23, 30, June 6, 13, 20, July 18, 25, August 1, 22, 29, September 12 and 19.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The **1889 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1889.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the New York Giants and the Brooklyn Bridegrooms as regular season champions of the National League and American Association, respectively.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the sixth World's Championship Series on October 18 and ended with Game 9 on October 29, in what was a best-of-eleven-playoff.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants defeated the Dodgers, six games to three, capturing their second consecutive World's Championship Series.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Over the offseason, the National League's Detroit Wolverines folded, and saw them replaced by the American Association's Cleveland Blues, renamed to the Cleveland Spiders.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] In Cleveland's AA place, the Columbus Solons were enfranchised.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] This was the final season of the NL's Indianapolis Hoosiers & Washington Nationals, and the AA's Kansas City Cowboys.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The 1889 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American Association since the 1886 season and by the National League since the previous season.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring four teams, while National League Opening Day took place on April 24, featuring all eight teams.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 15 with four teams playing, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 5, featuring all eight teams.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The 1889 World's Championship Series took place between October 18 and October 29.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams of the American Association (which was informally referred to as the "Beer & Whiskey League" due to its openness on alcohol, compared to the National League) to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Initial version of stadium burned in a fire in mid-May and was rebuilt in time before the need for a neutral site.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] 26 tie games (13 in AA, 13 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The Columbus Solons join the American Association and play at Recreation Park in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Following their eviction from the original Polo Grounds in New York, New York over the offseason, the New York Giants would play at several ballparks while waiting for their next home further uptown, also called the Polo Grounds, to finish construction.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The team would play at Oakland Park in Jersey City, New Jersey for two games on April 24 and 25, before beginning play at the St.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] George, New York, the former home of the New York Metropolitans, where they played from April 29 through June 14.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Following a road trip, the team would begin play at the new Polo Grounds on July 8.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] A fire at Washington Park, home of the Brooklyn Bridegrooms occurred on May 17 while the team was on a road trip.
[src:connie-mack/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The burnt down grandstand and fencing were rebuilt in time for the team to play their next scheduled home game, on May 30.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The **1890 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1890.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and newly founded Players' League regular seasons ended on October 4, with the Boston Beaneaters and Boston Reds as the NL and PL pennant winners, respectively.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association regular season ended on October 15 and saw the Louisville Colonels the winners of the AA pennant.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the AA and NL began with Game 1 of the seventh World's Championship Series on October 17 and ended with Game 7 on October 28.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The series ended in a tie, with the Bridegrooms and Colonels each with three wins, and a tie game.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The series was unique in that the Bridegrooms reached the series back-to-back, but with each season in a different league, a feat that has not been matched since.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The Reds had floated a three-way Championship series with them and the AA & NL pennant winners, though the idea fell on deaf ears.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] This was the final season of a dual-league championship until the founding of the modern World Series in 1903 between the National League and American League.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The major league world was in turmoil in 1890, as many of the best players had jumped to the "outlaw" Players' League.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] Although the Brotherhood only lasted the one season, it had a detrimental financial effect on the other two leagues, especially the Association, who would not survive the following season, merging into the National League in December 1891.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] Over the prior offseason, the Indianapolis Hoosiers and Washington Nationals of the National League, and Kansas City Cowboys of the American Association folded.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The major-league status of the Federal League was confirmed by the Special Baseball Records Committee (as convened by then-Commissioner of Baseball William Eckert) in 1969.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American Association, National League, and Players' League, each of which had eight active teams (the Baltimore Orioles would finish the Brooklyn Gladiators' schedule once they folded following their last game on August 25).
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American Association since the 1886 season and by the National League since the 1888 season.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring six teams, while National League and Players' League Opening Days took place on April 19, each featuring their eight teams.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 15 with a doubleheader between the Baltimore Orioles and Rochester Broncos.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the season on October 4, with a doubleheader between the Philadelphia Phillies and Cleveland Spiders.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The Players' League would see its season end on the same day, with all eight teams playing.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 World's Championship Series took place between October 17 and October 28.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 season featured an extremely rare tripleheader—the first of three in National League and major-league history, when the Brooklyn Bridegrooms hosted the Pittsburgh Alleghenys on September 1 for three games.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Gladiators, Cleveland Spiders, and Pittsburgh Alleghenys played in 17 neutral site games in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] 31 tie games (15 in AA, 9 in NL, 7 in PL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] Only records for National League teams are available.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] With the Brooklyn Bridegrooms transferring to the National League, which bans Sunday games, their three-season tenure playing Sunday games at Ridgewood Park in Ridgewood, New York ends.
[src:connie-mack/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 season saw six teams playing at their respective ballparks for the last time, five of which moved into new ballparks for the start of the 1891 season while one team, the Brooklyn Gladiators, folded mid-season.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The **1891 major league baseball season** was contested from April 8 through October 6, 1891.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] It was the final season for the American Association (AA), with the Boston Reds winning the AA pennant.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The Reds, following the 1890 Brooklyn Bridegrooms consecutive pennant wins 1889–1890 in different leagues, also followed such a feat, winning the since folded Players' League's 1890 pennant and becoming the second and last team to win consecutive pennants in different leagues.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season since 1883 which saw no postseason, due to a breakdown in relations between the American Association and National League prior to the start of the season.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The next championship series would take place the following season in a unique split season format, due to negotiations during the merger of the AA into the NL.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The unstable American Association would see that 1891 would be its final season, before merging into the National League the following season; the four clubs that would continue on were the Baltimore Orioles, Louisville Colonels, St.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The other four AA clubs, the Boston Reds, Columbus Solons, Milwaukee Brewers, and Philadelphia Athletics), saw their owners paid $135,000 (equivalent to $4,837,500 in 2025) and their players dispersed to the surviving twelve clubs.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The 1891 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight active teams (the Milwaukee Brewers would finish the Cincinnati Kelly's Killers' schedule once they folded following their last game on August 16).
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American Association since the 1886 season and by the National League since the 1888 season, and was the last season this format would be used until the National League contracted from twelve to eight teams in 1900.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 8 featuring all eight teams, while National League Opening Day would not take place for another two weeks on April 22, also featuring all eight teams.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 6, while the National would see its final day of the season on October 3.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The Milwaukee Brewers hosted a neutral site game in Minneapolis, Minnesota against the Columbus Solons.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] 19 tie games (12 in AA, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in *italics* indicates a team a player was on from a different league.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] Any stat from said different league is not calculated to determine the league leader.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Colts begin playing at South Side Park, splitting their season from West Side Park.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] They would play their final game at West Side Park on October 2 against the Cincinnati Reds, permanently moving into South Side Park for the start of the 1892 season.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] American Park, the home of the Cincinnati Reds, is renamed to League Park.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] After the Cincinnati Outlaw Reds folded mid-season, the Milwaukee Brewers withdrew from the Western League as a replacement team, playing at Brewer Field.
[src:connie-mack/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The team plays one of their 21 home games at a neutral site in Athletic Park in Minneapolis, Minnesota.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The **1894 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1894.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Baltimore Orioles as the pennant winner of the National League and the New York Giants as runner-up.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first Temple Cup on October 4 and ended with Game 4 on October 8.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants swept the Orioles, capturing their first Temple Cup.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the Temple Cup, following the end of the World's Championship Series with the demise of the American Association in 1891 and the one-off, split-season 1892 World's Championship Series.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place in the previous season and would be used until 1898.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring eight teams.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, also featuring eight teams.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 4 and October 8.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Makeshift stands built for remainder of the season, from August 18.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the start of the season, the Cincinnati Reds' home as League Park saw major changes.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] A new grandstand in what was left field was built, as well as an ampitheater.
[src:connie-mack/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The baseball diamond was shifted from the southeast corner of the lot to the southwest corner, with the original seating retained as right field seating.
[src:connie-mack/1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1894 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the 13th season of the Pittsburgh Pirates franchise; their eighth in the National League.
[src:connie-mack/1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates finished seventh in the National League with a record of 65–65.
[src:connie-mack/1895-major-league-baseball-season] The **1895 major league baseball season** began on April 18, 1895.
[src:connie-mack/1895-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Baltimore Orioles as the pennant winner of the National League and the Cleveland Spiders as runner-up.
[src:connie-mack/1895-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the second Temple Cup on October 2 and ended with Game 5 on October 8.
[src:connie-mack/1895-major-league-baseball-season] The Spiders defeated the Orioles, four games to one, capturing their first Temple Cup.
[src:connie-mack/1895-major-league-baseball-season] The 1895 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:connie-mack/1895-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since 1893 and would be used until 1898.
[src:connie-mack/1895-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 18 featuring ten teams.
[src:connie-mack/1895-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring six teams.
[src:connie-mack/1895-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 2 and October 8.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack managed the Philadelphia Athletics for its first 50 seasons of play, starting in 1901; was at least part-owner from 1901 to 1954; and retired after the 1950 season at age 87.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He was the first American League manager to lead a team to 100 wins, doing so in 1910, 1911, 1929, 1930, and 1931; his five 100-win seasons are second-most in MLB history, with only two other managers surpassing him.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He was the first manager to win the World Series three times, and he is the only manager to win consecutive Series on two occasions (1910–11, 1929–30); his five Series titles remain the third-most by any manager, and his nine American League pennants rank second in league history.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] However, constant financial struggles forced repeated rebuilding of the roster, and Mack's teams also finished in last place 17 times, including ten seasons in which the Athletics lost 100 games.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack was elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame in 1937.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack was born Cornelius McGillicuddy on December 22, 1862, in Brookfield, Massachusetts, in what is now East Brookfield.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] His parents, Michael McGillicuddy and Mary McKillop, were immigrants from Ireland: Michael from Killarney in County Kerry, and Mary from the Catholic section of Belfast.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] A wheelwright by trade, Michael served with the 51st Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry Regiment during the American Civil War.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He suffered from several ailments as the result of his military service; after the war, he was able to work only infrequently and drew a disability pension.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] As with many Irish immigrants whose names began with "Mc", the McGillicuddys were often referred to as "Mack", except in official and legal documents.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Michael’s father was named Cornelius McGillicuddy, and by tradition, the family named at least one son in each generation Cornelius.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] "Connie" is a common nickname for Cornelius, so Cornelius McGillicuddy was called "Connie Mack" from an early age.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He did not have a middle name, but many accounts erroneously give him the middle name "Alexander"; this error probably arose because his son Cornelius McGillicuddy Jr. took Alexander as his confirmation name.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Connie Mack never legally changed his name; on the occasion of his second marriage at age 48, he signed the wedding register as "Cornelius McGillicuddy".
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] His nickname on the baseball field was "Slats", for his height of 6 feet 2 inches and thin build.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack was educated in East Brookfield, and began working summers in local cotton mills at age 9 to help support his family.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He quit school after completing the eighth grade at age 14, intending to work full-time to contribute to the family's support, as several of his siblings had done.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He clerked at a store, worked on local farms, and worked on the production lines of the shoe factories in nearby towns.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack was also a good athlete and frequently played baseball and some of its predecessor games with local players in East Brookfield.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In 1879 his skills landed him a place on East Brookfield's town team, which played other town teams in the area.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Though younger than his teammates by several years, Mack was the team's catcher and *de facto* captain.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Beginning in 1886, Mack played 10 seasons in the National League and one in the Players' League, for a total of 11 seasons in the Major Leagues, mainly as a catcher.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Beginning in 1884, he played on minor league teams in the Connecticut cities of Meriden and Hartford.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack was sold to the Washington Nationals (sometimes called the Statesmen or the Senators) of the National League in 1886.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In the winter of 1889, he jumped to the Buffalo Bisons of the new Players' League, investing his entire life savings of $500 in shares in the club.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] But the Players' League went out of business after only a year, and Mack lost his job and his whole investment.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In December 1890 Mack signed a contract with the Pittsburgh Pirates of the National League and remained with them for the rest of his career as a full-time player.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack was one of the first catchers to position himself directly behind home plate instead of in front of the backstop.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] According to Wilbert Robinson, "Mack never was mean ... [but] if you had any soft spot, Connie would find it.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In addition to verbally needling batters to distract them, he developed skills such as blocking the plate to prevent base runners from scoring and faking the sound of a foul tip.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] (He was probably responsible for the 1891 rule change requiring that a batter must have two strikes against him in order to be called out if the catcher caught a foul tip.) Besides tipping bats to fake the sound of a foul tip, Mack became adept at tipping bats to throw off the hitter's swing.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] ("Tipping" a bat is to brush it with the catcher's mitt as the batter swings, either delaying the swing or putting it off course, so that the batter misses the ball or does not hit it solidly.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack's last three seasons in the National League were as a player-manager with the Pittsburgh Pirates from 1894 to 1896, with a 149–134 (.527) record.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack was fired on September 21, 1896, retiring as a full-time player.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack accepted a deal from Henry Killilea to act as manager and occasional backup catcher for the minor league Milwaukee Brewers (the modern-day Baltimore Orioles).
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He managed the Brewers for four seasons from 1897 to 1900, their best year coming in 1900, when they finished second, behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] It was in Milwaukee that he first signed pitcher Rube Waddell, who would follow him to the big leagues.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] On November 8 1900, Mack became manager of the new American League's then unnamed Philadelphia ballclub, which eventually became known as the Athletics.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Shortly after, he would be named treasurer and part owner of that said franchise.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack managed the Athletics through the 1950 season, compiling a record of 3,582–3,814 (.484) when he retired at 87.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack won nine pennants and appeared in eight World Series, winning five.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack's 50-year tenure as Athletics manager is the most ever for a coach or manager with the same team in North American professional sports, and has never been seriously threatened.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Joe Paterno, with 62 seasons as a college football coach for the Penn State Nittany Lions also surpassed Mack, although Paterno was head coach in only 46 of those years.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] College football pioneer Amos Alonzo Stagg also surpassed Mack in overall tenure, though not in tenure for a single employer; he was a head coach for 55 seasons in all (1892–1946), with the first 41 at Chicago (1892–1932).
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack was widely praised in the newspapers for his intelligent and innovative managing, which earned him the nickname "the Tall Tactician".
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He valued intelligence and "baseball smarts," always looking for educated players.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] According to baseball historian Bill James, Mack was well ahead of his time in having numerous college players on his teams.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Several of his players went on to become well-respected college coaches.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Jack Coombs, the ace of Mack's 1910–11 champions, became the longtime coach at Duke.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Andy Coakley, who won 20 games for Mack's 1905 pennant winners, coached for over 30 years at Columbia, where he was the college coach for Lou Gehrig.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Dick Siebert, longtime coach at Minnesota, played for Mack from 1938 to 1945.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] James believed that Mack's influence on the game, as great as it was, would have been even greater had the college game been more popular during the 1920s and 1930s, when Mack was at his peak.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He also looked for players with quiet and disciplined personal lives, having seen many players in his playing days destroy themselves and their teams through heavy drinking.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack himself never drank; before the 1910 World Series he asked all his players to "take the pledge" not to drink during the Series.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In any event, his managerial style was not tyrannical but easygoing.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He never imposed curfews or bed checks, and made the best of what he had.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Rube Waddell was the best pitcher and biggest gate attraction of Mack's first decade as the A's manager, so he put up with his drinking and general unreliability for years, until it began to bring the team down and the other players asked Mack to get rid of Waddell.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Unlike most other baseball managers, Mack chose to wear a business suit and overcoat in the dugout rather than a team uniform.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack's strength as a manager was finding the best players, teaching them well and letting them play.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] "He did not believe that baseball revolved around managerial strategy." He was "one of the first managers to work on repositioning his fielders" during the game, often directing the outfielders to move left or right, play shallow or deep, by waving his rolled-up scorecard from the bench.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] After he became well known for doing this, he often passed his instructions to the fielders by way of other players, and simply waved his scorecard as a feint.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Over the course of his career, he had nine pennant-winning teams spanning three peak periods or "dynasties." His original team, with players such as Rube Waddell, Ossee Schrecongost, and Eddie Plank, won the pennant in 1902 (when there was no World Series) and 1905.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] They lost the 1905 World Series to the New York Giants (four games to one, all shutouts, with Christy Mathewson hurling three shutouts for a record 27 scoreless innings in one World Series).
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] During that season, Giants manager John McGraw said that Mack had "a big white elephant on his hands" with the Athletics.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack defiantly adopted the white elephant as the team's logo, which the Athletics still use today.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] As that first team aged, Mack acquired a core of young players to form his second great team, which featured Mack's famous "$100,000 infield" of Eddie Collins, Home Run Baker, Jack Barry and Stuffy McInnis.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] That team was dispersed due to financial problems, from which Mack did not recover until the 20s, when he built his third great team.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The 1927 Athletics featured several future Hall of Fame players including veterans Ty Cobb, Zack Wheat and Eddie Collins as well as young stars like Mickey Cochrane, Lefty Grove, Al Simmons and rookie Jimmie Foxx.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Louis beat the A's in seven games led by Pepper Martin.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] That team was dispersed after 1932 when Mack ran into financial difficulty again.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] By 1934, the A's had fallen into the second division.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Although Mack intended to rebuild for a third time, he would never win another pennant.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The Athletics' record from 1935 to 1946 was dismal, finishing in the basement of the AL every year except a 5th-place finish in 1944.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] World War II brought further hardship due to personnel shortages.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In 1938, Mack in his middle seventies successfully battled a blood infection caused when a batted ball injured one of his shinbones.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He stopped for treatment at the Medical and Surgical Hospital in San Antonio, Texas, where he was in passage on a train.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In addition, as Mack entered his 80s, his once-keen mind began fading rapidly.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack would make strange decisions (which his coaches and players usually overruled), make inexplicable outbursts, and call for players from decades earlier to pinch-hit.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He spent most games asleep in the dugout, leaving his coaches to run the team most of the time.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] According to Bill James, by the time Mack recovered again financially, he was "old and out of touch with the game, so his career ends with eighteen years of miserable baseball." It was generally agreed that he stayed in the game too long, hurting his legacy.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He was unable to handle the post-World War II changes in baseball, including the growing commercialization of the game.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] His business style was no longer viable in post-World War II America due to various factors, including the increased expense of running a team.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] For instance, he never installed a telephone line between the bullpen and dugout.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Despite the circumstances, the octogenarian Mack led the team to three winning seasons in 1947–1949 (including a fourth-place finish in 1948).
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] With the A's unexpected resurgence in 1947–1949, there was hope that 1950—Mack's 50th anniversary as the A's manager—would bring a pennant at last.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] However, the A's never recovered from a dreadful May in which they only won five games.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] By May 26, the A's were 11–21, 12 games out of first, and it was obvious the season was a lost cause.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] On that date, his sons Earle, Roy and Connie, Jr. persuaded their father to promote Jimmy Dykes, who had been a coach since 1949, to assistant manager for the remainder of the season.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Dykes became the team's main operator in the dugout, and would take over the managerial reins in his own right in 1951.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] At the same time, Cochrane was named general manager—thus stripping Connie, Sr. of his remaining authority.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Six weeks after his mid-season retirement, Mack was honored by baseball when he threw out the ceremonial first pitch of the 1950 All-Star Game.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The American League's white knight, Charles Somers, provided the seed money to start the Athletics and several other American League teams.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] However, plans called for local interests to buy out Somers as soon as possible.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] To that end, Mack persuaded sporting goods manufacturer Ben Shibe, a minority owner of the rival Philadelphia Phillies, to buy a 50 percent stake in the team—an offer sweetened by Mack's promise that Shibe would have the exclusive right to make baseballs for the American League.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In return, Mack was allowed to buy a 25 percent stake, and was named secretary and treasurer of the team.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Two local sports writers, Frank Hough and Sam Jones, bought the remaining 25 percent, but their involvement was not mentioned in the incorporating papers; in fact, no agreement was put on paper until 1902.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack and Shibe did business on a handshake.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In 1913, Hough and Jones sold their 25 percent to Mack, making him a full partner in the club with Shibe; Mack actually borrowed the money for the purchase from Shibe.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Under their agreement, Mack had full control over baseball matters while Shibe handled the business side.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] However, Mack had enjoyed more or less a free hand over the baseball side since the team's inception.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] When Shibe died in 1922, his sons Tom and John took over management of the business side, with Tom as team president and John as vice president.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Tom died in 1936, and John resigned shortly thereafter, leaving Mack to take over the presidency.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] John Shibe died in 1937, and Mack bought 141 shares from his estate, enough to make him majority owner of the A's.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] However, he had been operating head of the franchise since Ben Shibe's death.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Such an arrangement is no longer possible in current times, as major-league rules do not allow a coach or manager to own *any* financial interest in a club.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack's great strength as owner was his network of baseball friends, all of whom acted as scouts and "bird-dogs" for him, finding talented players and alerting Mack; "Mack was better at that game than anybody else in the world.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] People liked Mack, respected him, and trusted him. ...
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack saw baseball as a business, and recognized that economic necessity drove the game.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He explained to his cousin, Art Dempsey, that "The best thing for a team financially is to be in the running and finish second.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Unlike most baseball owners, Mack had almost no income apart from the A's.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Even when he collected rent from the Phillies, he was often in financial difficulties.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The war hurt the team badly, leaving Mack without the resources to sign valuable players.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] His 1916 team, with a 36–117 record, is often considered the worst team in American League history, and its .235 winning percentage is still the lowest ever for a modern-era (since 1900) major league team.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The team's 117 losses set a modern-era record and at the time were the second most losses behind the Cleveland Spiders' 130 in 1899.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] As of 2024 that record has been topped only three times, all by teams that played 162-game schedules, not 154 like the Athletics: the 1962 New York Mets (120 losses in their inaugural season), the 2003 Detroit Tigers (119 losses), and the 2024 Chicago White Sox (121 losses).
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] All told, the A's finished dead last in the AL seven consecutive seasons (1915 to 1921), and would not reach .500 again until 1925.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The rebuilt team won back-to-back championships in 1929–1930 over the Cubs and Cardinals, and then lost a rematch with the latter in 1931.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] As it turned out, these were the last postseason appearances for the A's not only in Philadelphia, but for another four decades.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Unlike with the breakup of his second great team, the A's did not tumble out of contention right away.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] They remained fairly competitive for most of the first half of the 1930s.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] However, after 1933, they would only tally four more winning seasons during their stay in Philadelphia—which would be the franchise's only winning seasons for 35 years.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] With the 1929 onset of the Great Depression, Mack struggled financially again, and was forced to sell the best players from his second great championship team, such as Lefty Grove and Jimmie Foxx, to stay in business.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Although Mack wanted to rebuild again and win more championships, he was never able to do so owing to a lack of funds.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Even before then, he either did not (or could not) invest in a farm system.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack celebrated his 70th birthday in 1932, and many began wondering if his best days were behind him.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Even as bad as the A's got during the next two decades, he stubbornly retained full control over baseball matters long after most teams had hired a general manager.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] This continued even after he became majority owner, despite calls both inside and outside Philadelphia to step down.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Indeed, one of the few times that Mack considered giving up even some of his duties was in the 1934–35 offseason—when the A's were still not far removed from what would be their last great era.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He briefly entertained replacing himself as manager with Babe Ruth, but ruled that idea out, saying that the Babe's wife, Claire, would be running the team inside of a month.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In the early 1940s, Mack gave a minority stake in the team to his three sons, Roy, Earle, and Connie, Jr.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Although Roy and Earle had never gotten along with Connie, Jr., who was more than 20 years younger than them, Connie, Sr. intended to have all three of them inherit the team after his death or retirement.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] This strategy backfired when Roy and Earle refused to consider Connie, Jr.'s demands to end the team's bargain-basement way of doing business.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] One of the few things on which they agreed was that it was time for their father to step down.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Connie, Jr. was only able to force through other minor improvements to the team and the rapidly crumbling Shibe Park through an alliance with the Shibe heirs.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] When it became apparent that his older brothers were not willing to go further, Connie, Jr. and the Shibes decided to sell the team.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] However, Roy and Earle countered by buying out their younger brother, persuading their father to support them.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In order to pull off the deal, however, they mortgaged the team to the Connecticut General Life Insurance Company (now part of CIGNA).
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Yearly payments of $200,000 drained the team of badly needed capital, and ended any realistic chance of the A's winning again under the Macks' stewardship.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] When Mack resigned as manager, he largely withdrew from active control of the team.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Over the next five years, the team crumbled to the bottom of the American League.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Although reduced to a figurehead, Mack continued to be treated with awe and reverence by players who considered him living history.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] His sons handled his correspondence by 1953 as he had become too frail by that point to do it himself.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] As that year ended, the A's were dangerously close to bankruptcy.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The other American League owners had been concerned for some time about the situation in Philadelphia, since the crowds at Shibe Park had dwindled to the point that visiting teams could not meet their expenses for traveling there.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Prior in 1951, Buffalo based businessman and Sportservice owner Louis Jacobs gave Mack a loan of $250,000.00 with no interest to keep the Athletics from having financial difficulty.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The 1954 A's attracted only 304,000 people, nowhere near enough to break even.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The other owners, as well as league president Will Harridge, wanted the Athletics sold off to a new owner.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The Yankees in particular lobbied for it to be Chicago businessman Arnold Johnson (1906–1960), who had recently bought both Yankee Stadium as well as Blues Stadium in Kansas City, home to the Yankees' top Triple AAA farm team in the second American Association.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Roy and Earle Mack did not want to move the team, but pressure from the Yankees and blowback from several bad business decisions finally moved their hand and they agreed to the sale.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] A final attempt to sell the A's to Philadelphia car dealer John Crisconi briefly gained Mack's support, but collapsed at the eleventh hour—reportedly due to behind-the-scenes intrigue by the Yankees.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] When that deal collapsed, a bitter Mack wrote a letter blasting his fellow owners for sinking the Crisconi deal.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] However, he admitted that he did not have nearly enough money to run the A's in 1955, and conceded that the Johnson deal was the only one with a chance of approval.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In early November, Mack agreed to sell the A's to Johnson for $1.5 million.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The aforementioned Louis Jacobs helped broker the deal between the Mack family and Johnson.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] When the American League owners met in New York to discuss the sale to Johnson, they voted 5–3 to approve the sale.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Johnson immediately requested permission to move to Kansas City, which was granted after Detroit's Spike Briggs switched his vote.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Although Mack had long since conceded that his 55 years in the American League were over, his doctor reported that the nonagenarian owner suffered a sudden sharp drop in blood pressure and almost expired upon learning that his team was gone.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The A's sold Shibe Park, now renamed Connie Mack Stadium, to the Phillies.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack was still chauffeured around to games by his caretaker.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He attended the 1954 World Series and the occasional regular season game, but in October 1955, he fell and suffered a hip fracture.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack underwent surgery on October 5, missing the World Series that week for the first time ever.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He required the use of a wheelchair after that point, celebrating his 93rd birthday in November.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] His death came at his daughter's house on the afternoon of February 8, 1956.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] According to his doctor, he'd been fine until the 7th when he "just started to fade away".
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Officially, it was announced that he died of "old age and complications from his hip surgery" Mack's funeral was held in his parish church, St.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Bridget's, and he was buried in Holy Sepulchre Cemetery in Cheltenham Township just outside Philadelphia, with Commissioner of Baseball Ford Frick, the AL and NL presidents, and all 16 MLB owners serving as pallbearers.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack was quiet, even-tempered, and gentlemanly, never using profanity.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] He always called his players by their given names.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Chief Bender, for instance, was "Albert" to Mack.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Perhaps due to his great longevity in the game, he appeared to have a kind of saintly image; his long-time friends objected to the image of him as "the bloodless saint so often painted, a sanctimonious old Puritan patting babies".
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] His friend Red Smith called him "tough and warm and wonderful, kind and stubborn and courtly and unreasonable and generous and calculating and naive and gentle and proud and humorous and demanding and unpredictable".
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Beginning as far back as his first managing job in the 19th century, Mack drew criticism from the newspapers for not spending enough money.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Some writers called him an outright miser, accusing him of getting rid of star players so he could "line his own pockets" with the money.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] However, his biographer Norman Macht strongly defends Mack on this question, contending that Mack's spending decisions were forced on him by his financial circumstances, and that nearly all the money he made went back to the team.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] After reading this, Mack told his players that if they won Game Five he would give them the team's entire share of the Game Five gate receipts—about $34,000.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The Athletics won the game and the series, and Mack gave out the money as promised.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack supported a large extended family and was generous to players in need, often finding jobs for former players.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] For instance, he kept Bender on the team payroll as a scout, minor league manager or coach from 1926 until Mack himself retired as owner-manager in 1950.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Simmons was a coach for many years after his retirement as a player.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The Athletics did not have a black player until Bob Trice in 1953, three years after Mack retired as manager.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The Philadelphia stadium, originally called Shibe Park, was renamed Connie Mack Stadium in 1953.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Starting in 1909, it was home to the Athletics, and starting in 1938, it also was home to the Phillies, then from 1955 to 1970 was home to the Phillies alone, after the Athletics moved to Kansas City.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] There is a Connie Mack Street in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] On November 2, 1887, Mack married Margaret Hogan, whom the *Spencer Leader* described as having "a sunny and vivacious disposition." They had three children, Earle, Roy, and Marguerite.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Margaret died in December 1892 after complications from her third childbirth.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack married a second time on October 27, 1910.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] His second wife was Catherine (or Katharine) Holahan (or Hoolahan) (1879–1966); the census records have various spellings (the wedding register reads "Catarina Hallahan").
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] The couple had four daughters and a son, Cornelius Jr.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] A faithful Catholic his entire life, Mack was also a longtime member of the Knights of Columbus (Santa Maria Council 263 in Germantown, which moved to Flourtown, Pennsylvania in the 1980s).
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] Mack's son Earle Mack played several games for the A's between 1910 and 1914, and also managed the team for parts of the 1937 and 1939 seasons when his father was too ill to do so.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] In more recent years, his descendants have taken to politics: Mack's grandson Connie Mack III was a member of the U.S.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] House of Representatives from Florida (1983–89) and the United States Senate (1989–2001); and great-grandson Connie Mack IV served in the U.S.
[src:connie-mack/connie-mack] House of Representatives (2005–13), representing Florida's 14th congressional district.
